Problem Statement ¶

Business Context: ¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective: ¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description ¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

  1. Those with higher education may want to travel abroad for a well-paid job. Does education play a role in Visa certification?

  2. How does the visa status vary across different continents?

  3. Experienced professionals might look abroad for opportunities to improve their lifestyles and career development. Does work experience influence visa status?

  4. In the United States, employees are paid at different intervals. Which pay unit is most likely to be certified for a visa?

  5. The US government has established a prevailing wage to protect local talent and foreign workers. How does the visa status change with the prevailing wage?

# Function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top
    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """
    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        hue=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )
    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot
        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage
    plt.show()  # show the plot


# Function to plot histograms and boxplots
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 6), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined
    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    (
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins)
        if bins
        else sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram


# function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart
    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()


# Function to create distribution plot
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title(f"Distribution of target for target={str(target_uniq[0])}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title(f"Distribution of target for target={str(target_uniq[1])}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Answers ¶

1. Those with higher education may want to travel abroad for a well-paid job. Does education play a role in Visa certification?¶

The stacked_barplot will allow us to see the distribution of certified and denied cases among applicants from different educational backgrounds. This will help us determine if education plays a significant role in visa outcomes.

In [17]:

Data Preparation for Modeling ¶

  • Our goal is to use machine learning to predict visa approvals, which involves handling a classification problem.
  • Before we proceed to build a model, we'll have to encode categorical features.
  • We'll split the data into train and test to be able to evaluate the model that we build on the train data.
  • When classification problems exhibit a significant imbalance in the distribution of the target classes, it is good to use stratified sampling to ensure that relative class frequencies are approximately preserved in train and test sets.
  • This is done using the stratify parameter in the train_test_split function.

Model Building ¶

Model Criterion - F1 Score ¶

Model can make wrong predictions as the following:¶

  1. The model predicts that the visa application will get certified, but in reality, the visa application should be denied. False Positive.
  2. The model predicts that the visa application will not get certified, but in reality, the visa application should be certified. False Negative.

Which case is more important?¶

  • Both cases are important in terms of reducing the losses because:

    • If a visa is certified when it should have been denied, an unqualified employee may fill the position, while U.S. citizens miss the opportunity to work in that role.
    • If a visa is denied when it should have been certified, the U.S. will lose a valuable human resource that could contribute to the economy.

How to reduce the losses?¶

  • The F1 Score can be used as the metric for model evaluation. A higher F1 score increases the likelihood of minimizing both False Negatives and False Positives.
  • We will use balanced class weights so that the model focuses equally on both classes.

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot the confusion matrix.
In [33]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [34]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Decision Tree - Model Building and Hyperparameter Tuning ¶

  • Gini Impurity is a metric used to evaluate the “purity” of a node in a decision tree. It quantifies the likelihood of an incorrect classification of a randomly chosen element from a dataset, based on the distribution of classes in that node.
  • In the context of our problem, where we want to predict whether a visa application will be certified or denied, we need to create decision rules that best separate the two classes (Certified vs. Denied) at each node in the tree.
  • Since we want to make the most accurate predictions about whether a visa application will be certified or denied. By choosing splits that minimize Gini Impurity, the decision tree is making the "cleanest" separations between Certified and Denied applications.
  • A split with low Gini Impurity would mean that for most cases within that node, the model can confidently predict the outcome. For example, if a node after a split predominantly contains Certified applications, the model has learned a strong pattern.

Decision Tree - Hyperparameter Tuning ¶

Note

  1. Sample parameter grids have been provided to do necessary hyperparameter tuning. These sample grids are expected to provide a balance between model performance improvement and execution time. One can extend/reduce the parameter grid based on execution time and system configuration.

  • For Decision Trees:

In [38]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
dtc_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(2, 6),
    "min_samples_leaf": [1, 4, 7],
    "max_leaf_nodes": [10, 15],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.0001, 0.001],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search with n_jobs = -1 to use all available processors
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dtc_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the grid_obj on the training data
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the dtc_tuned to the best combination of parameters
dtc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
dtc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

  • The model correctly predicted all cases in the training set, indicating it fits the training data perfectly. However, this suggests that the model is still overfitting on the training data.
  • The model is making some mistakes, particularly with false positives (predicting certification when it should be denied) and false negatives (predicting denial when it should be certified), but the performance is now more realistic and better balanced.
  • The F1 score on the test set has improved significantly to 0.808, indicating a better balance between precision and recall. The overfitting seen in the training performance is still present, but the test performance is much more realistic and useful.
  • While the performance on the training and test set are still not as comparable, among the test models that have been built, the Bagging Classifier with hyperparameter tuning is the best performing model.

# from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
# from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
# from sklearn import metrics

# Choose the type of classifier.
rfc_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, oob_score=True, bootstrap=True)

parameters = {
    "n_estimators": [50, 110, 25],
    "min_samples_leaf": np.arange(1, 4),
    "max_features": [np.arange(0.3, 0.6, 0.1), "sqrt"],
    "max_samples": np.arange(0.4, 0.7, 0.1),
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search with cv = 5 and n_jobs = -1
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rfc_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the grid_obj on the training data
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
rfc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
rfc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

recall_test = []

precision_test = []
f1_train = []
f1_test = []

for model in models:
    # Get metrics for training data
    train_perf = model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, X_train, y_train)
    # Get metrics for test data
    test_perf = model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, X_test, y_test)

    # Append the metrics to respective lists with adjusted rounding
    train_acc.append(np.round(train_perf["Accuracy"][0], 4))
    test_acc.append(np.round(test_perf["Accuracy"][0], 4))
    recall_train.append(np.round(train_perf["Recall"][0], 4))
    recall_test.append(np.round(test_perf["Recall"][0], 4))
    precision_train.append(np.round(train_perf["Precision"][0], 4))
    precision_test.append(np.round(test_perf["Precision"][0], 4))
    f1_train.append(np.round(train_perf["F1"][0], 4))
    f1_test.append(np.round(test_perf["F1"][0], 4))

acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(xgbc_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
xgbc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
xgbc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

Overall Observations on Model Performance:¶

Decision Tree Models:

  • The basic Decision Tree model has perfect training performance (likely overfitting), but its test performance is lower, with a test F1 score of 0.734.
  • The tuned Decision Tree shows a balanced performance between training and testing, though it’s still modest in both areas.

Bagging Classifier Models:

  • The basic Bagging Classifier overfits slightly, but after tuning, it shows a significant improvement in test F1 score to 0.808, indicating a better generalization.

Random Forest Models:

  • The Random Forest model performs well with a perfect training score, but its test performance is lower, with a test F1 score of 0.801.
  • The tuned Random Forest model improves test F1 score to 0.816, suggesting that tuning has successfully reduced overfitting.

AdaBoost Models:

  • The AdaBoost model, especially after tuning, performs well, showing a test F1 score around 0.819, making it a strong candidate.

Gradient Boosting Models:

  • Both default and tuned Gradient Boosting models show strong performance with F1 scores around 0.820, indicating they are well-suited for the problem.

XGBoost Models:

  • XGBoost models, both default and tuned, demonstrate strong performance. The tuned XGBoost model achieves a test F1 score of 0.820, making it one of the top-performing models.

Best Model Selection:

Top Choice: Tuned XGBoost Model

The tuned XGBoost model is the best choice overall, balancing high test accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 score. It demonstrates robustness and generalizes well to unseen data, which is crucial for the business context. Runner-Up: Tuned Gradient Boosting Model

The tuned Gradient Boosting model is a close second, with similar performance metrics. It might be a preferred option if computational efficiency or interpretability is a concern.

Will tuning the hyperparameters improve the model performance? ¶

Yes, as seen in the overall model performance, tuning the hyperparameters improved in the majority of cases all the models.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations ¶

Understand the Problem:¶

  • Problem Analysis: The problem at hand is the increasing volume of visa applications, which is making the manual review process labor-intensive and inefficient. In FY 2016, the OFLC processed nearly 776,000 applications for almost 1.7 million positions, a number that continues to grow annually. Given the rising demand, a machine learning-based solution is necessary to assist in shortlisting candidates with a higher likelihood of visa approval.
  • Objective: Our goal is to develop a machine learning model that can accurately predict visa approvals, thereby streamlining the application review process. Additionally, we aim to recommend a suitable profile for applicants, highlighting key factors that significantly influence the visa certification decision.

Based on the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):¶

  • Visa Certification by Continent: The analysis indicates variability in visa certification rates across different continents. While Asia submits the most applications, Europe exhibits a higher certification rate. Recommendation: Prioritize recruitment in regions with higher certification rates, such as Europe, while optimizing processes for high-volume regions like Asia to increase approval rates.

  • Impact of Education Level on Visa Status: Higher education levels, particularly Master's and Doctorate degrees, correlate with increased chances of visa certification. Recommendation: Focus on recruiting candidates with advanced degrees to improve the likelihood of visa approval, aligning with the preference for highly educated applicants.

  • Job Experience and Training: Applicants with job experience have a higher visa approval rate, while the need for job training does not significantly impact the decision. Recommendation: Recruit candidates with relevant job experience and provide necessary training, as experience is a key determinant of visa success.

  • Region of Employment: The certification rate varies across US employment regions, with some regions showing higher approval rates. Recommendation: Consider the region of employment during the hiring process, targeting regions with historically higher visa approval rates.

  • Wage Considerations: Offering a competitive yearly salary is associated with higher visa certification rates. Recommendation: Ensure that foreign workers are offered salaries that align with or exceed the prevailing wage, particularly on a yearly basis, to increase the likelihood of approval.

Based on the Modeling Results:¶

  • Model Performance: The classification model effectively predicts visa certification outcomes based on key applicant and employer features, such as education, job experience, and wage. Recommendation: Integrate the model into the visa application review process to prioritize high-probability candidates, thereby enhancing efficiency and accuracy in decision-making.

  • Optimizing Recruitment: The model's predictions can help identify high-potential candidates earlier in the recruitment process, reducing resources spent on processing applications likely to be denied. Recommendation: Utilize model insights to develop a data-driven recruitment strategy that focuses on candidates with the best chances of visa approval, aligning with business objectives to remain competitive in the talent market.

This comprehensive approach, grounded in data analysis and modeling, will enable OFLC and EasyVisa to optimize the visa approval process, making it more efficient and aligned with strategic business goals.

Business Recommendations:¶

1. Automate the Screening Process¶

  • Leverage the Classification Model: Integrate the machine learning model into the visa application process to automate the initial screening of candidates. This can significantly reduce the manual workload and focus human resources on the more complex cases that require detailed analysis.
  • Continuous Model Improvement: Establish a process for continuous learning, where the model is retrained periodically with new data. This will help the model adapt to changes in visa approval patterns and improve accuracy over time.

2. Enhance Data Collection¶

  • Standardize Data Entry: Ensure that all data related to visa applications is collected in a standardized format. This includes structured input for categorical data (e.g., education level, job experience) to improve the model's performance.
  • Expand Data Sources: Incorporate additional data sources that could influence visa approvals, such as economic indicators, company financials, or employee testimonials. These additional features could provide deeper insights and improve model accuracy.

3. Candidate Profile Optimization¶

  • Profile Recommendations: Use insights from the model to provide feedback to visa applicants. For instance, suggest potential improvements in their profiles (e.g., gaining relevant job experience, pursuing higher education) to increase their chances of visa approval.
  • Education and Training Programs: Partner with educational institutions and training centers to offer courses that align with the skills and experiences that are highly valued in the visa approval process.

4. Policy Advocacy¶

  • Inform Policy Changes: Share insights from the model with policymakers to help shape future visa regulations. For example, if certain education levels or job experiences are consistently leading to visa approvals, these could be prioritized in immigration policies.
  • Predictive Policy Impact: Use the model to simulate how potential changes in visa policies might affect approval rates. This can help in making data-driven decisions at the policy level.

5. Customer-Centric Services¶

  • Applicant Support Services: Develop services that assist visa applicants in preparing their profiles. This could include resume building, interview coaching, and document preparation services to ensure their applications meet the requirements highlighted by the model.
  • Real-Time Feedback: Provide real-time feedback to applicants during the application process, helping them understand their approval probability based on current model predictions, and offering suggestions for improvement if necessary.

6. Performance Monitoring and Reporting¶

  • Develop Dashboards: Create dashboards that allow stakeholders to monitor the performance of the machine learning model over time. This can include metrics like accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 scores across different applicant categories.
  • Regular Reports: Provide regular reports to management and policymakers, summarizing trends in visa approvals and denials, and highlighting any shifts that could be of concern.

# Define the dummy columns for 'continent'
continent_cols = [col for col in df_eda.columns if "continent" in col]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5 * len(continent_cols)))
for i, variable in enumerate(continent_cols):
    # Statistical summary
    summary = (
        df_eda.groupby(variable)["case_status"]
        .value_counts(normalize=True)
        .unstack()
        .fillna(0)
        * 100
    )
    plt.subplot(len(continent_cols), 2, 2 * i + 2)
    sns.heatmap(summary, annot=True, cmap="Blues", fmt=".1f")
    plt.title(f"Statistical Summary for {variable}")
    plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

Observations:

  • Employees from Europe and Africa have slightly lower certification rates compared to other continents.
  • Asia, which has the highest number of applicants, also has a relatively high certification rate.
